ike in red and run) and /u/ ('oo' in boot)). Constrictions in oral cavity.Less dramatically tied to vowels than F1/F2, but:         /i/ ('ee') tends to have a higher F3. /u/ ('oo') and /r/ ('rr') tends to have a lower F3.          F4: Cis Women [3500 - 5000] Hz | Cis Men [2800 - 3700] Hz: Speaker and Timbre Characteristics. Not directly vowel-diagnostic. Affected by:         Vocal tract length, Voice quality, Subtle articulation cues. Used more in voice profiling (e.g., gender, vocal effort) and not vowel identification.  ">
